I'll guide you through getting Google API credentials (Client ID and Client Secret) for implementing "Login with Google" using Laravel Socialite.

📋 Step-by-Step Guide to Get Google OAuth Credentials
Step 1: Access Google Cloud Console
Go to the Google Cloud Console: https://console.cloud.google.com

Sign in with your Google account (use the same account you want to manage your app)

Step 2: Create or Select a Project
At the top of the page, click on the project dropdown menu (it might say "Select a project" or show a current project name)

Click New Project to create a new project, or select an existing one

If creating a new project:

Enter a Project name (e.g., "My Laravel App")

Leave the other fields as default or fill as needed

Click Create

Step 3: Configure OAuth Consent Screen
This is a required step before you can create credentials :

In the left sidebar, navigate to APIs & Services → OAuth consent screen

Choose the user type:

External: Anyone with a Google account can log in (recommended for most public apps)

Internal: Only users in your Google Workspace organization (if applicable)

Fill in the required information:

App name: Your application name (e.g., "My Laravel App")

User support email: Select your email from the dropdown

Developer contact information: Your email address

Authorized domains: Add your app's domain (e.g., localhost for development, or yourdomain.com for production)

Click Save and Continue

Step 4: Add Scopes (Optional)
On the Scopes page, you can add specific permissions your app needs:

.../auth/userinfo.email - View your email address

.../auth/userinfo.profile - View your basic profile info

openid - OpenID Connect authentication

Click Save and Continue

Step 5: Add Test Users (For External apps in Testing mode)
If your app is in "Testing" mode, add test user emails

Click Save and Continue

Step 6: Create OAuth Client ID
Now let's create the actual credentials :

In the left sidebar, go to APIs & Services → Credentials

Click Create Credentials at the top

Select OAuth client ID from the dropdown

Step 7: Configure Application Type
For Application type, select Web application

Enter a Name for this client (e.g., "Laravel Socialite Client")

Step 8: Add Authorized Redirect URIs
This is critical - the redirect URI must match exactly what you'll use in Laravel :

Click Add URI under "Authorized redirect URIs" and add:

text
# For local development
http://localhost:8000/auth/google/callback
http://localhost:8000/auth/google/callback/

# For production
https://yourdomain.com/auth/google/callback
https://yourdomain.com/auth/google/callback/
Important notes :

The URI must match exactly (including trailing slash or not)

For testing, it's safe to add both versions (with and without trailing slash)

Localhost URLs work for development but won't work in production

Step 9: Get Your Credentials
Click Create

A dialog box will appear with your:

Client ID

Client Secret

Copy both immediately and save them securely

You can always view them later by going to Credentials and clicking on your OAuth 2.0 Client ID

📝 Adding Credentials to Laravel
Add these to your .env file:

env
GOOGLE_CLIENT_ID=your-client-id-here
GOOGLE_CLIENT_SECRET=your-client-secret-here
GOOGLE_REDIRECT_URI=http://localhost:8000/auth/google/callback
Then update config/services.php:

php
'google' => [
    'client_id' => env('GOOGLE_CLIENT_ID'),
    'client_secret' => env('GOOGLE_CLIENT_SECRET'),
    'redirect' => env('GOOGLE_REDIRECT_URI'),
],
⚠️ Important Notes
App Publishing Status
New apps start in "Testing" mode - only test users you added can log in

For production use with all users, you'll need to:

Complete any verification steps Google requires
Set the app status to "In production" in OAuth consent screen settings
Common Issues & Solutions
"redirect_uri_mismatch" error

Double-check the exact URL in Google Console matches what's in your .env file

Check for trailing slashes (both versions can be added for safety)

"Access blocked: This app's request is invalid"

Complete all required fields in the OAuth consent screen

Add your domain to authorized domains

"This app isn't verified" warning

For testing, users can click "Advanced" → "Go to [App Name] (unsafe)"

For production, go through Google's verification process

